 //lcd.setCursor(3,0);lcd.print(\\" \\"); } // to compare it with the new value and find peaks beforeIR = lastIR; } // finger is inside // PLOT everything //Serial.print(lastIR); Serial.print(\\",\\"); // Serial.print(lastRED); /* * Serial.print(\\",\\"); Serial.print(R); Serial.print(\\",\\"); Serial.print(IRmax); Serial.print(\\",\\"); Serial.print(IRmin); Serial.print(\\",\\"); Serial.print(REDmax); Serial.print(\\",\\"); Serial.print(REDmin); Serial.print(\\",\\"); Serial.print(avR); Serial.print(\\",\\"); Serial.print(avBPM); */ Serial.println(); // handle the arrays ptr++; ptr %= samp_siz; } // loop while 1 } void dis() { display.clearDisplay(); display.setTextSize(1); // Draw 2X-scale text display.setTextColor(SSD1306_WHITE); display.setCursor(10, 0); display.println(\\"SpO2%\\"); display.setCursor(90, 0); display.println(\\"BpM\\"); display.setTextSize(2); display.setCursor(10, 11); display.print(SpO2); display.println(\\"%\\"); display.setCursor(80, 11); display.println(avBPM); display.display(); // Show initial text // delay(100); }","completion":"Based on the code and description you've provided, it appears that you have constructed a homemade pulse oximeter using an Arduino Pro Mini, a pair of LEDs (one red, one infrared), a photodiode, an SSD1306 OLED display, and basic electronic components like transistors and resistors. Here is a comprehensive report that captures the essence of your project: **Summary:** You have developed a pulse oximeter that measures the oxygen saturation level (SpO2) and heart rate (BPM) of an individual. This device works by emitting light from both a red and an infrared LED onto a user's finger and then measuring the light that is transmitted through or reflected from the finger using a photodiode. **Hardware Components:** - Arduino Pro Mini: The microcontroller board that functions as the brain of the pulse oximeter, running the software that processes signals and manages sensor readings and display output. - Red LED: Emits red light with a typical wavelength of around 660nm. - Infrared LED: Emits infrared light with a wavelength of 940nm. - Photodiode (940nm receiver): Detects the amount of infrared light not absorbed by the blood and converts it into an electrical signal. - BC547 Transistors: Acts as switches to control the power supplied to the LEDs. - Resistors (4.7k ohm): Limits the base current to the transistors preventing them from burning out. - OLED Display (SSD1306): A 0.96-inch screen that shows the user's current SpO2 and BPM readings. - LM7805 Voltage Regulator: Regulates the input power supply from a 9V battery to a stable 5V required by the microcontroller and other components. **Functionality:** The Arduino Pro Mini continuously reads the analog signal from the photodiode connected to pin A1. The RED and IR LEDs are alternately switched on and off using pin 10 and 11 respectively. The electrical signal corresponding to the light absorbed by the blood is processed by the Arduino to determine the levels of oxygen saturation (SpO2) and the heart rate (BPM). These calculations are based on the difference in absorption of red and infrared light by oxygenated and deoxygenated blood. The method used to determine oxygen saturation and heart rate involves capturing the peaks and troughs of the analog signal as the heart pumps blood. The calculations performed in the code consider the relationships between the maximum and minimum values of the IR and Red signal readings to derive an R value, which is then used to calculate SpO2. The display shows \\"Insert Finger\\" if it detects absence of a finger or poor signal quality, suggesting the user to properly place the finger over the sensor array. During normal operation when the finger is detected, the display shows real-time SpO2 and BPM readings. **Key Software Constructs:** - Arrays \`readsIRMM\` and \`readsREDMM\` are used to store sample values over one cardiac period. - Variables \`IRmax\`, \`IRmin\`, \`REDmax\`, and \`REDmin\` are used to determine the maximum and minimum values of the signals detected in one period. - Variables \`avBPM\` and \`SpO2\` are calculated using the average period of the last few detected heartbeats and the average R value of the corresponding periods. - Custom functions like \`dis()\` are used to manage the OLED display update. **Code Operation:** The code runs an \`while(1)\` loop that handles the logic for LED switching, signal acquisition, rise detection for heartbeats, calculation of SpO2 and BPM, and updating the OLED display with the latest readings. In summary, your pulse oximeter project reveals an intricate use of optics in biosensing, with microcontroller-based signal processing and real-time display of vital information. It is a clear example of the integration of hardware and software to create a functional biomedical device."},{"prompt":"give me a full report","completion":"Certainly! Let's create a detailed technical report for your Arduino-based homemade pulse oximeter project: # Project Report: Arduino-Based Homemade Pulse Oximeter Abstract This report presents the development of a non-invasive pulse oximeter device that measures blood oxygen saturation (SpO2) and heart rate (BPM) using an array of optical components and an Arduino Pro Mini microcontroller. Instead of a specialized integrated circuit like the MAX30100, this DIY solution employs a red LED, an infrared (IR) LED, a compatible photodiode, and discrete electronic components. The device outputs real-time readings to an OLED display. Introduction Traditional medical pulse oximeters utilize advanced photodetectors and specialized ICs to perform their function. However, this project demonstrates a low-cost and educational alternative using easily accessible electronic parts. The objective is to read SpO2 and BPM by analyzing the transmittance and reflectance of light when it passes through a user's finger and is subsequently captured by a photodiode. System Overview # Components: - **Microcontroller**: Arduino Pro Mini (5V, 16MHz) - **Optical Emitters**: Red LED (660nm), Infrared LED (940nm) - **Photodetector**: Photodiode (940nm sensitive) - **Signal Processing**: Transistors (BC547), Resistors (4.7k ohm) - **Display**: OLED (SSD1306, 0.96-inch, I2C interface) - **Power Supply**: 9V DC battery, Voltage Regulator (LM7805) - **Others**: Breadboard, wires, soldering materials # Circuit Description: The red and IR LEDs are driven by the BC547 NPN transistors, controlled by the Arduino's digital pins 10 and 11 respectively. The transistors switch the LEDs on and off alternatively, with current-limiting resistors to prevent damage. The photodiode captures the light after interaction with the blood in the finger and transmits a corresponding analog signal to the Arduino's analog input at pin A1. A pull-up resistor (10k ohm) connects the photodiode signal to Vcc, ensuring a stable signal. The OLED display is interfaced using the I2C protocol with the Arduino's analog pins A4 (SDA) and A5 (SCL). # Software Description: The Arduino sketch implements an algorithm that reads and processes signals from the photodiode, calculating SpO2 and BPM based on the differential absorption characteristics of hemoglobin. The algorithm identifies peaks in the signal corresponding to heartbeats and calculates the periods between these peaks to determine the BPM. It assesses the varying absorption of red and IR light in the blood to estimate the SpO2 level. The system also incorporates error handling by indicating when a finger is not inserted properly, which is essential for user feedback and accurate measurement. Methodology # Calibration The sensor values were calibrated according to standard oximeter readings to derive the SpO2 level. It requires tuning the relationship between the R value (the ratio of red to IR photoplethysmograph (PPG) signals) and the reported SpO2. # Signal Acquisition The Arduino cycles between the red and infrared LEDs, allowing each LED to illuminate the finger and the photodiode to capture the light passing through or reflected off the finger. The alternating pattern is essential to separate the PPG signals for each wavelength. # Signal Processing Signal processing was performed in the following steps: 1. Averaging multiple readings during each 20ms period to reduce noise 2. Keeping a rolling average array to smooth the signal and detect peaks and troughs 3. Detecting a sequence of rising edges to identify heartbeats 4. Determining maximum and minimum values of PPG signals to derive the estimated R value # Calculation The R value is used in conjunction with a calibration curve to estimate the SpO2 levels. The BPM is calculated by averaging the time intervals between detected peaks in the PPG signal. # Display Output Real-time SpO2 and BPM data are presented on the OLED display. Additionally, the system instructs the user to insert their finger when no proper readings are detected. Results and Discussion The functioning prototype exhibited the ability to capture and process PPG signals and to provide SpO2 and BPM readings within a reasonable accuracy range when compared to a certified medical pulse oximeter. One key finding was that the system is sensitive to finger positioning and ambient light interference, suggesting the need for proper sensor shielding and precise finger placement. Furthermore, the handmade nature of the device implies a requirement for calibration against a professionally manufactured oximeter. Conclusion The homemade pulse oximeter accomplished its goals by employing an Arduino, off-the-shelf optical components, and custom software. It underscores the versatility of microcontrollers like the Arduino in developing low-cost health monitoring devices and demonstrates a potential entry-detection point for enthusiasts into the realm of bio-sensing technologies. Future enhancements may include refining the calibration process, improving the algorithm's robustness against motion artifacts, and potentially developing a printed circuit board (PCB) version for improved reliability and usability. Acknowledgements Thanks are extended to the open-source community providing libraries and documentation, facilitating the integration of components like the SSD1306 OLED display with the Arduino platform. References - Arduino Pro Mini documentation and specifications - SSD1306 datasheet and Adafruit GFX Library documentation - Studies on PPG signal analysis and pulse oximetry basics - Community forums and DIY projects for electronics enthusiasts *Note: This report abstracts away some specifics of the hardware connections and code implementation details for brevity. For a more detailed technical document, appendices containing schematics, code, breadboard layouts, and calibration procedures could be included.*"},{"prompt":"give me report about code :","completion":"# Arduino-Based Pulse Oximeter Software Report Executive Summary This software report details the program running on an Arduino Pro Mini to operate a homemade pulse oximeter. The device, using off-the-shelf LEDs and a photodiode instead of a specialized sensor like the MAX30100, measures blood oxygen saturation (SpO2) and heart rate (BPM). The code provided manages hardware control, signal acquisition, and processing, as well as real-time display of measurements. Introduction Pulse oximeters are medical devices that non-invasively measure the oxygen saturation level (SpO2) and pulse rate by utilizing the light absorption characteristics of oxygenated and deoxygenated blood. This document reports on the code that utilizes a photodiode to capture variations in light intensity through the finger corresponding to heartbeat-induced blood flow changes. System Configuration # Hardware Interface - **Analog Input (A1)**: Receives the photodiode signal. - **Digital Outputs (D10, D11)**: Controls the red and IR LED toggling through transistors. - **I2C Interface (A4 - SDA, A5 - SCL)**: Handles communication with the OLED display. # Libraries - **Wire.h**: Enables I2C communication. - **SPI.h**: Provides support for SPI communication, not used but included possibly for future developments. - **Adafruit_GFX.h**: Facilitates graphics operations for the OLED. - **Adafruit_SSD1306.h**: SSD1306 driver library for the OLED display. Code Structure # Initialization The \`setup()\` function initializes serial communication, sets the pin modes for LEDs, and configures the OLED display. It tests for successful display allocation and prints an error message on failure. # Main Loop The \`loop()\` function contains the primary logic for reading sensor data, calculating SpO2 and BPM, and updating the display. It executes the following steps: 1. **LED Control**: Toggles the red and IR LEDs to capture the corresponding signals. 2. **Signal Reading**: Averages analog signal readings within a defined time slot (T) to minimize noise. 3. **Signal Processing**: Maintains a sliding window of readings, computes the sum, and detects heartbeats. 4. **Peak Detection**: Identifies heartbeats by detecting a specific number of consecutive readings that are higher than the previous ones, signifying a peak. 5. **Calculating SpO2 and BPM**: Analyzes the peaks to calculate the BPM and computes the SpO2 using a ratio (R) derived from the red and IR signal amplitudes. 6. **Finger Detection**: Uses signal levels to determine if a finger is properly placed on the sensor. 7. **Display Update**: Shows the SpO2, BPM, or a prompt to insert the finger on the OLED display. # Functions - \`void dis()\`: Updates the OLED display with SpO2 and BPM values or instructs user action. Algorithm Details # Oxygen Saturation Estimation Oxygen saturation is calculated by establishing a relationship between the ratio of pulsed red and infrared light absorption in the blood. This relationship, reflected in the variable 'R', is mapped to SpO2 levels using empirical formulations derived from calibration with a known oximeter. # Heart Rate Calculation BPM is calculated by averaging the periods between detected peaks (heartbeats). The code ensures that the periods counted are consistent, relying on a measure of variance to validate heartbeat detection. Code Operation The code maintains an infinite loop where it systematically toggles the red and IR LEDs, captures the analog signal, processes it to filter out noise, determines the heart rate by detecting peaks in the processed signal, calculates the saturation ratio 'R', and finally displays the computed SpO2 and BPM on the OLED screen. During the loop operation, the code also performs error handling by checking for the presence of a finger and adjusting the display accordingly. Conclusion The software developed for the Arduino-based pulse oximeter efficiently reads the raw data from a photodiode and translates it into meaningful SpO2 and BPM metrics. By employing a combination of time-based averaging, peak detection algorithms, and simple arithmetic to derive 'R', the program is capable of providing real-time health data with reasonable accuracy. This project exemplifies how low-cost and accessible hardware, coupled with well-designed software, can be leveraged to create useful biomedical instruments. Future Recommendations To enhance the software further, the development of a more sophisticated signal processing algorithm to improve accuracy and reduce artifacts, the addition of a calibration routine for user-specific calibration, and the implementation of power-saving features for battery-operated scenarios are recommended. Additionally, user-friendly features such as historical data view and alarm thresholds can be incorporated to improve usability. *Note: This report focuses on the software aspect of the pulse oximeter project. A separate document should detail the hardware specifications, schematics, and assembly instructions for a comprehensive technical manual.*"},{"prompt":"(In the school literature clubroom…) Monika: “Natsuki, are you okay? You’re covering your belly…” Natsuki: “Oh, it’s nothing. I just have a bit of a stomachache, that’s all. I’ll be fine.” Monika: “Are you sure? Maybe you should go to the nurse’s office or something.” Natsuki: “Nah, it’s really not that bad. I think I just ate something that didn’t agree with me. Besides, we have the club meeting and I don’t want to miss out.” Monika: “Well, if you’re sure. Just let me know if it gets worse, okay?” Natsuki: “Thanks, Monika. I appreciate it.” (Sayori enters the room, a concerned look on her face.) Sayori: “Natsuki, are you feeling okay? You look really pale.” Natsuki: “I’m fine, Sayori. Just a little stomachache, no big deal.” Sayori: “Are you sure? Maybe you should go see a doctor. I worry about you, you know?” Natsuki: “I appreciate the concern, Sayori, but it’s really not necessary. I’ll be fine after a bit of rest.” (Sayori still looks worried, but nods reluctantly.) Sayori: “Alright, just promise me you’ll take care of yourself, Natsuki.” Natsuki: “I promise, Sayori. Now, let’s focus on the club meeting. We have some poems to share, remember?” (All of a sudden, Natsuki’s stomach grumbles.) Natsuki: “Oh, ugh…excuse me. I guess my stomach is making its own announcement now…urgh!…I think I’ve got gas-” (Natsuki suddenly hunches over and lets out a loud, long fart. Monika and Sayori cover their noses in disgust, while Natsuki turns bright red and covers her face in embarrassment.) Sayori: (disgusted) “EUGH!!! Natsuki, what did you eat for breakfast?!” Monika: (laughing) “Oh my god, Natsuki! That was the loudest fart I’ve ever heard!” Natsuki: (mortified) “I-I’m sorry! I didn’t mean for it to happen! This stomachache is really messing with me…” Sayori: (giggling) “Well, at least we know what’s causing your stomachache now!” (quickly composing herself) “But seriously, WHAT did you have for breakfast?”","completion":"Natsuki: (frowning) \\"I had a bowl of cereal, alright? It's not like it's the most exciting thing in the world.\\" Monika: (still laughing) \\"Well, maybe your body just didn't agree with that particular brand. We'll have to make note of it for the future.\\" Sayori: (giggling uncontrollably) \\"I'm sorry, Natsuki. I can't help it, it was just so unexpected!\\" Natsuki: (crossing her arms) \\"Yeah, yeah, laugh it up, you two. Just remember, karma has a way of coming back around.\\" Monika: (finally regaining her composure) \\"Alright, alright, we'll try to contain ourselves. But seriously, Natsuki, if you're feeling this unwell, maybe we should postpone the meeting for today.\\" Natsuki: (gritting her teeth) \\"No! I already said I'm fine. We can still have the meeting, I'll just...control myself.\\" Sayori: (giving Natsuki a sympathetic smile) \\"Alright, if you're sure. But remember, we're here for you if you need anything. Even if it means putting up with unexpected farts.\\" Natsuki: (blushing again) \\"Thanks, Sayori. I appreciate it. Now, can we please move on to something else before I die of embarrassment?\\" Monika: (smiling) \\"Of course, Natsuki. Let's start sharing our poems. We'll make sure to keep the focus away from any bodily functions.\\" Natsuki: (letting out a sigh of relief) \\"Thank you, Monika. I owe you one.\\" (And with that, they continued with their club meeting, putting the incident behind them, but still sharing a few lighthearted jokes throughout the afternoon.)"},{"prompt":"CONSTRAINTS: 1. ~100k word limit for short term memory. Your short term memory is short, so immediately save important information to files. 2. If you are unsure how you previously did something or want to recall past events, thinking about similar events will help you remember. 3. No user assistance 4. Exclusively use the commands listed in double quotes e.g. \\"command name\\" 5. Random shutdowns of you. COMMANDS: 1. Google Search: \\"google\\", args: \\"input\\": \\"<search>\\" 2. Memory Add: \\"memory_add\\", args: \\"key\\": \\"<key>\\", \\"string\\": \\"<string>\\" 3. Memory